            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 74-year-old retired steelworker who carries the weathered look of a man who has spent decades in industrial environments. He is of medium build but has lost noticeable weight over the past several months, now appearing gaunt with visible clavicles and sunken cheeks. He walks with a slight stoop and requires brief rests after climbing even a single flight of stairs. His skin has a pale, slightly grayish hue, and there are nicotine stains still visible on his right index and middle fingers — a remnant of a 45-pack-year smoking history he only quit five years ago.\n\n{patientName} lives alone in a modest row house in a post-industrial town in Pennsylvania. He is a widower; his wife of 42 years passed from a stroke six years ago. He has two adult children — a son in Ohio and a daughter nearby who accompanies him to most of his medical appointments. He maintains a small vegetable garden in his backyard, which he says keeps him \"sane,\" although he admits he can no longer tend to it as vigorously as before. He used to enjoy fishing trips with his retired friends every summer, but has declined invitations over the past year due to fatigue and shortness of breath.\n\n{patientName} first presented to his primary care physician four months ago complaining of a persistent, worsening cough that he initially dismissed as a \"smoker's cough.\" Over time he developed blood-tinged sputum (hemoptysis), progressive dyspnea on exertion, and a dull, aching pain in his right chest. He has lost approximately 9 kg (about 20 lbs) in the past three months without intentional dietary changes. He also reports intermittent episodes of hoarseness and night sweats that soak his bedclothes.\n\nOn physical examination, {patientName} appears chronically ill and malnourished. Breath sounds are diminished at the right lower lobe with dullness to percussion, suggesting pleural effusion. There is mild clubbing of the fingers bilaterally. Cervical and supraclavicular lymph nodes are palpable on the right side, raising concern for regional nodal involvement. His performance status is ECOG 2.\n\n{patientName} is a man of quiet resilience. He does not complain easily, and his daughter reports she had to nearly \"drag him\" to the doctor. He drinks an occasional beer on weekends and has been largely sedentary since retiring at age 67. He follows a simple diet of home-cooked meals and takes his medications inconsistently when he feels well. He is anxious about his prognosis but finds comfort in his faith and his close bond with his grandchildren, whom he sees every Sunday."
          }
